  <li id="comment-45953" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Karen</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-45953"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-02-20T17:11:01-05:00">Saturday, February 20, 2016 at 5:11 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>This is great, Molly (I love your blog and books too by the way!) especially the advice on not fetishising food/cooking and not making it the enemy either, just making it normal. I wanted to ask a question about whether you manage to all eat as a family every night, what time you eat, is it sometimes just you and June, does she need to eat early and Brandon and you later? I only ask because I&#8217;ve grappled with this a lot over the years &#8211; my kids are now 12 and 8 but the 8 year old wants to eat early (latest 6), my 12 year old son eats kind of constantly but prefers to eat with my husband and myself but my husband gets home later (very erratic hours in film and television, almost as bad as the restaurant industry I suspect) and as a couple we used to eat around 8pm or later.  Also I had great intentions to always eat at a well-set table and did when the kids were smaller or when I was pregnant with my second and happy to adopt a kid-mealtime routine as I was so exhausted (and not drinking wine!) but as the years have gone by it&#8217;s slightly fallen apart with lots of TV suppers (albeit home-cooked ones) partly because my husband wants to just crash when he gets home from work. I&#8217;m trying hard to get back to a better dinnertime routine (it&#8217;s compounded also by increased fussiness from two kids who ate anything when they were June&#8217;s age&#8230;&#8230;grrrrrr) but I don&#8217;t know what time to set it at  and was interested how others managed.</p>
    </div>

      <ol class="children">
  <li id="comment-46014" class="comment byuser comment-author-molly bypostauthor even depth-2">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://orangette.net" class="url" rel="ugc">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-46014"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-02-22T17:23:18-05:00">Monday, February 22, 2016 at 5:23 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>For us, it&#8217;s kind of a work in progress.  Brandon has been working mostly in the daytime for the past several months, as he prepares to open Dino&#8217;s, and it&#8217;s meant that we all get to eat dinner together most of the time. We usually eat between 6 and 7, and I let June have a snack beforehand to tide her over. And dinner is often really simple stuff: a soup I made over the weekend, rice from the rice cooker with whatever greens are in the fridge and a fried egg on top and nuoc cham, or fried rice, or scrambled eggs and whatever (carrot sticks dipped in vinaigrette is a crowd-pleaser here). But when Brandon is working at night, it&#8217;s sort of a toss-up. About half the time, I feed June, put her to bed, and then eat on my own. Or I take her to Delancey! We have an easy out, for better or for worse&#8230;</p>
<p>In any case, I think you&#8217;re doing a fantastic job. It sounds like you do manage to eat together quite a bit, and to cook at home, despite being busy!  Your kids are very lucky.</p>
    </div>

