      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://webloomhere.blogspot.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Margaret Bloom</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-46005"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-02-22T13:29:38-05:00">Monday, February 22, 2016 at 1:29 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I started cooking with my boys when they were old enough to stand on a chair, too.  A resounding yes to all the suggestions on your list  except I still really hate allowing my 5 y.o. to crack eggs, and I limit his jam usage by apportioning out a tablespoon, or so, into a small bowl from whence he can apply his jam&#8230; or not apply it, as is the case on days he prefers a deconstructed sandwich (i.e. eating first the jam, then the peanut butter and then finally the bread).</p>
<p>Also, my one of my favorite tools for rolling out cookies with my children has been a rolling pin with rings on the ends to keep consistent thickness for the rolled out dough.  I have a pin with wooden rings but, in case you&#8217;re interested, these ones do exactly the same job <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Evendough-rolling-pin-bands-sets/dp/B004QP5EME/" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.amazon.com/Evendough-rolling-pin-bands-sets/dp/B004QP5EME/</a></p>
<p>Cheers!<br />
mb</p>
