  <li id="comment-46064" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Caroljay</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-46064"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-02-25T11:16:43-05:00">Thursday, February 25, 2016 at 11:16 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>My earliest memories are of being that three-year-old, safely perched on my chair, next to my Mom&#8217;s shoulder, watching and helping her to cook.  And, as you mentioned, it was mostly everyday dinners, and weekend breakfasts.   My job (and any interested siblings&#8217;), was to sort (things like beans and berries), or to break up bread, crack eggs, etc.  I also learned how to measure out ingredients, how to add seasonings (&#8220;&#8230;not too much, because you can always add, but it&#8217;s hard to take it out&#8230;&#8221;), and how to mix and stir.   On Saturday and Sunday, we carefully woke my Dad with a precariously-held cup of coffee, and then we would all proceed to the kitchen for eggs and bacon and pancakes (or waffles, or French toast&#8230;).  These things are indelible; I am 54 years old, both of my parents are gone now, and yet I remember cooking with them as if it were yesterday.  We continued these traditions with my sister&#8217;s kids (the only grandkids), and we totally did the cookie thing, with my sister, niece, nephew, and I forming a production line for making everything from meatballs to gingerbread cookies.  Each of us, including the kids, had their own aprons, and everyone shared in the cleanup.  My niece is now 24, and employed as a chef in Ireland.  And my memories are awesome&#8230;  ðŸ˜‰</p>
    </div>

