  <li id="comment-46065" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Mags</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-46065"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-02-25T12:13:47-05:00">Thursday, February 25, 2016 at 12:13 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>My two-year-old is completely involved in our cooking. This wasn&#8217;t exactly by design on my part; we just cook breakfast and dinner at home every day, usually when only one parent is available, and it&#8217;s been easier to entertain a child by involving him than having him crying outside of the kitchen or at your feet. The most important part of this is a stool we have that&#8217;s original purpose was to allow me to reach high shelves and now is completely his (last night I had to grab a chair from the dining room to get a dutch oven from a high shelf because sharing is not my son&#8217;s thing). He does all that you have mentioned here (well the only cutting he&#8217;s mastered is bananas) and a few more things, some of which make me nervous (but it&#8217;s easier to let him drop pasta in boiling water one by one with close supervision than dealing with a tantrum &#8212; even though this means that the past will not all be perfectly al dente at once). </p>
<p>A favorite recipe for cooking together is your granola (number 5, but all done on the scale with very approximate measuring) because it&#8217;s fool proof, very quick, and yet feels special and we can talk about how he made it whenever we eat it.</p>
    </div>

