      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Erin</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-48445"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-03-17T22:12:37-04:00">Thursday, March 17, 2016 at 10:12 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Love these tips and ideas! We tend to stay away from cooking anything with raw eggs in it with our 3.5 yo as she likes to lick her fingers A LOT when in the kitchen.  Some other ideas that our 3.5 yo does at home-<br />
Peeling outer layers of leaves off Brussels sprouts<br />
Pulling mushroom caps off of stems<br />
Washing carrots<br />
Shredding cooked chicken for chicken salad<br />
Smashing eggs and then mixing egg salad</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-48622" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://wordpress.com/posts/herenowpage.wordpress.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Bronwyn</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-48622"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-03-18T10:49:08-04:00">Friday, March 18, 2016 at 10:49 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Dear Molly,<br />
Great post. I love your writing and always enjoy stopping by. I very much enjoyed your list of tips (no. 5 made me laugh out loud). So true.  Our girls go to a Montessori school, which I love for all the reasons you mentioned. It just makes sense. Our kids are now 5 and 7, but we&#8217;ve been cooking with them since they could sit on the counter. I wrote a post about it called, &#8220;Cooking with Children&#8221; awhile ago. There are some parallels to you thinking on the subject.<br />
Enjoy!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-49456" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://hungryenoughtoeatsix.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Nancy Mock</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-49456"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-03-21T20:52:46-04:00">Monday, March 21, 2016 at 8:52 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>These are great tips and observations on cooking with kids, and those pink cookies are lovely! I wholeheartedly agree that if you are going to invite a child to cook with you, you have to be willing to relax and let a whole lotta things slide (messes, sticking fingers into batter, wanting to be done when the first batch of cookies are out of the oven, messes.) I never wanted my kids to feel like making food was scary or a chore, so I invite them to cook with me often and let them do their thing. I was so proud the day I realized my daughter makes a much tastier guacamole than I do. And my son feels completely comfortable straying from a recipe to try his own variations. I think it&#8217;s great that you are encouraging the same curiosity and confidence in your daughter!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-49476" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Krysten</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/02/9390/#comment-49476"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-03-22T09:40:06-04:00">Tuesday, March 22, 2016 at 9:40 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I have found that my boys (1.5 and 5.5) will happily play with a small bowl of flour while I finish up almost any recipe. Yes, it makes a mess of the counter and floor, but they&#8217;re both going to need to be cleaned up anyway after cooking with kids.  We are liking making biscuits because I let them rub the butter into the dry ingredients with their fingers.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-51323" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
